value.value: The sum of raw scores from all recall exercises.

Mutated forms of genes which encode proteins that are essential for the control and maintenance of normal cellular processes. Inherited or somatic mutations in the wild-type form of these genes alters control of their expression, resulting in a change in control of the cell cycle. Individuals who harbor cancer-predisposing genes require fewer somatic mutations for transformation of a particular cell, thereby predisposing them to the development of cancer.
An indication of the number of intrusion errors in trials 1-5.
An indication of the number of intrusion errors during the free recall exercise.
An indication of the number of intrusion errors during the cued recall exercise.
The ability to distinguish target words from distractor words.

label.value: MAPK Pathway Activating Gene Alteration Positive

value.value: An indication that gene alterations that result in activation of the MAPK signaling pathway have been detected. Causative gene alterations include mutations resulting in the expression of BRAF p.V600E and gene fusions involving FGFR2 or FGFR3.

A deletion of chromosomal material on the long arm of chromosome 6 involving bands p23 through p26. This chromosomal aberration results in the expression of the MYB/QKI fusion gene and is associated with angiocentric glioma.
A fusion gene that results from a ~30kb deletion, del(6)(q23q26), that fuses the first 9 or 15 exons of the MYB gene to exon 5 of the QKI gene. This fusion is associated with angiocentric gliomas.

A fusion protein encoded by the MYB/QKI fusion gene. This protein is comprised of the N-terminus of transcriptional activator Myb protein, including the helix-turn-helix (HTH)-type DNA binding domain and the transactivation domain (long variants resulting from fusions including exon 15 of the MYB gene also have a C-terminal negative regulatory domain), which is fused to the amino acids comprising the C-terminal half of protein quaking, which excludes the RNA binding KH domain but includes the QUA2 RNA binding and SH3-binding domains (both the long and short variants of this fusion protein may also include the QKI C-terminal nuclear localization sequence (NLS)).

label.value: Diffuse Low Grade Glioma, MAPK Pathway-Altered

value.value: A rare, low-grade diffuse glioma with morphological features of astrocytoma or oligodendroglioma, generally affecting children. It is characterized by a gene alteration that results in a MAPK pathway abnormality. The genetic abnormalities are typically a BRAF p.V600E substitution mutation, mutations or fusions involving the FGFR1 gene and internal tandem duplication (ITD) of the sequences of FGFR1 gene encoding the tyrosine kinase domain (TKD). The tumor is IDH-wildtype and does not have a homozygous deletion of CDKN2A gene.

label.value: Diffuse Low Grade Glioma, FGFR1 Tyrosine Kinase Domain-Duplicated

value.value: Diffuse low-grade glioma characterized by internal tandem duplications of the sequences in the FGFR1 gene encoding the tyrosine kinase domain.

A genetic marker phenotype found in some cancers, this condition is marked by the presence of hundreds to thousands of mutations in microsatellite regions of chromosomes. These mutations are associated with decreased fidelity of DNA replication.
Diffuse low-grade glioma characterized by FGFR1 gene mutations, an internal tandem duplication within the FGFR1 gene or the presence of an FGFR1 fusion gene.

label.value: Diffuse Low Grade Glioma, BRAF p.V600E-Mutant

value.value: Diffuse low-grade glioma characterized by the presence of BRAF gene mutations encoding a p.V600E substitution mutation.
A genetic finding indicating the presence of gene abnormalities resulting in alteration of signaling in the MAPK pathway.
An indication that internal tandem duplication within the FGFR1 gene has been detected in a sample.

label.value: FGFR1 Tyrosine Kinase Domain Internal Tandem Duplication Positive

value.value: A genetic finding that refers to internal tandem duplications of sequences in the FGFR1 gene encoding the tyrosine kinase domain.

label.value: Proton Pencil Beam Scanning Spatially-Fractionated Radiotherapy

value.value: Pencil beam scanning proton therapy that uses a grid structure to deliver high doses of radiation within a tumor, with regions of low dose exposure between beams.

An orally bioavailable, small molecule, reversible inhibitor of interleukin-1 receptor-associated kinase 4 (IRAK4), with potential immunomodulating and anti-inflammatory activities. Upon oral administration, zimlovisertib targets, binds to, and blocks the kinase activity of IRAK4. This inhibits IRAK4-mediated signaling, prevents the activation of IRAK4-mediated nuclear factor-kappa B (NF-kB) signaling and decreases the expression of inflammatory cytokines. This may inhibit inflammation and immune-mediated cell destruction in inflammatory and auto-immune diseases where toll-like receptor (TLR) or interleukin 1 receptor (IL-1R) signaling is overactivated and MYD88 is dysregulated. IRAK4, a serine/threonine-protein kinase that plays a key role in both the TLR and IL-1R signaling pathways, is activated though the adaptor protein MYD88 and links the TLR and IL-1R signaling pathway to the NF-kB pathway.

label.value: Aluminum Hydroxide Adjuvanted Inactivated SARS-CoV-2 Vaccine BBIBP-CorV

value.value: A vaccine composed of inactivated severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus-2 (SARS-CoV-2) HB02 strain and aluminum hydroxide, with potential immunizing activity against SARS-CoV-2. Upon administration, aluminum hydroxide adjuvanted inactivated SARS-CoV-2 vaccine BBIBP-CorV may provide active immunization and induce neutralizing antibodies against SARS-CoV-2, thereby protecting against SARS-CoV-2 infection. The aluminum hydroxide adjuvant improves antigen processing by the immune system.

An engineered protein subunit vaccine composed of an Fc fusion protein of the severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus-2 (SARS-CoV-2) spike (S) protein receptor binding domain (RBD) antigen and human immunoglobulin G1 (IgG1) Fc, with potential immunizing activity against SARS-CoV-2. Upon administration of the SARS-CoV-2 protein subunit vaccine AKS-452, the S protein activates the immune system to create anti-SARS-CoV-2 S protein antibodies. The antibodies recognize and neutralize the S protein and kill SARS-CoV-2. This prevents SARS-CoV-2 infection. S protein, usually found on the surface of SARS-CoV-2, plays an essential role in the infection pathway of the SARS-CoV-2 virus.
An immunohistochemical diagnostic test to evaluate the expression of VTCN1 protein in a tissue sample.
This gene plays a role in signal transduction and is associated with diabetes mellitus.
A change in the amino acid residue at position 1813 in the endoribonuclease Dicer protein where glutamic acid has been replaced by glycine.
A nucleotide substitution at position 5439 of the coding sequence of the DICER1 gene where guanine has been mutated to thymine.
A nucleotide substitution at position 5439 of the coding sequence of the DICER1 gene where guanine has been mutated to cytosine.
The process of shipping something from one facility to another, usually to a customer or end user, or to a more specialized facility.
The use of light in the near-infrared spectrum to generate autofluorescence in tissues.
A genetically heterogenous group of disorders characterized by low mitochondrial DNA in specific tissues resulting in impaired energy production.

An autosomal recessive subtype of mitochondrial depletion syndrome caused by mutation(s) in the TK2 gene, encoding thymidine kinase 2, mitochondrial. It is characterized by muscle weakness associated with mtDNA depletion in skeletal muscle.
An autosomal dominant subtype of developmental and epileptic encephalopathy caused by mutation(s) in the DNM1 gene, encoding dynamin-1.

An autosomal recessive condition caused by mutation(s) in the CARS2 gene, encoding probable cysteine--tRNA ligase, mitochondrial, resulting in a defect in the mitochondrial oxidative phosphorylation system. It is characterized by epileptic encephalopathy, and phenotypically variable clinical findings.

Endoscopic or robotic-assisted removal of the proximal half of the stomach, including the cardia and fundus, as well as a portion of the distal esophagus, with the goal of preserving partial gastric function.
This gene is involved in nucleotide metabolism and cell cycle control.
Surgical removal of the whole stomach along with a portion of the distal esophagus, proximal duodenum, and associated lymph nodes.

A chromosomal anomaly characterized by the partial duplication of the short arm of chromosome 2. The phenotype is highly variable but principally characterized by growth failure, global developmental delay, facial dysmorphism and ocular anomalies.

A usually autosomal dominant inherited metabolic disorder affecting the bony labyrinth of the inner ear. Morphologically, it is characterized by the presence of sharply demarcated active (otospongiotic) and inactive (sclerotic) bony areas. It is one of the most common causes of conductive hearing loss.
A chronic inner ear disorder affecting balance and hearing. Symptoms may include vertigo, tinnitus, and hearing loss.

A Y-linked genetic condition caused by mutation(s) in the USP9Y gene, encoding probable ubiquitin carboxyl-terminal hydrolase FAF-Y.  It is associated with male infertility secondary to nonobstructive azoospermia and hypospermatogenesis.
A familial phenotype characterized by a normal QT interval at rest, but major QT lengthening during catecholergic stimulation.

A digenic recessive condition caused by mutation(s) in the ADH5 gene accompanied by a specific mutation in the ALDH2 gene. It is characterized by global developmental delay, impaired intellectual development, bone marrow failure, and myelodysplastic syndrome.

label.value: Nucleotide Sequencing Read Quality Control Data

value.value: Data pertaining to quality control parameters for nucleotide sequencing read experiments.

label.value: Read Group Pairs on Different Chromosomes Data

value.value: Sequencing read quality control data detailing the number of pairs where one read is on one chromosome and the other read is on a different chromosome.
Sequencing read quality control data detailing the relative proportion of base mismatches that occurred during a nucleotide sequencing run.
This gene plays a role in multi-drug resistance and organic anion transport.
Sequencing read quality control data detailing the relative proportion of duplicate reads that occurred during a nucleotide sequencing run.
Sequencing read quality control data detailing the relative proportion of mapped reads detected during a nucleotide sequencing run.
The acronym for the type of center that is running a clinical program, trial or study.
The alphanumeric code assigned to an entity in the tenth version of the International Classification of Disease (ICD-10).
